---
// About / site manifesto (TC-401 / KAN-103).
//
// Charter decision D4: the two framing arguments once planned as standalone
// essays — "Every Map Is an Argument" and "The Seduction of Precision" — are
// absorbed here as the site's curatorial statement, so they never appear as
// separate essays. This page also introduces the seven-room cosmography and
// links each room individually.
import PortalLayout from '../layouts/PortalLayout.astro';
import { getEssays } from '../lib/registry';
import { ROOMS } from '../data/rooms';
const essays = await getEssays();
---

<PortalLayout
  title="About & Manifesto"
  description="Terra Chartarum is a portal for reading maps critically: every map is an argument, precision is a seduction with a cost, and the atlas is arranged as a cosmography of seven rooms."
>
  <section class="shell prose">
    <p class="eyebrow">About &amp; manifesto</p>
    <h1>A portal for reading maps critically</h1>
    <p>
      <strong>Terra Chartarum</strong> gathers a growing family of interactive visual essays about the
      history and politics of cartography. Each essay is an immersive, self-contained piece with its own
      art direction; the portal gives them a shared front door, a common navigation, and a cross-essay
      atlas — so several experiments read as one publication rather than several tabs.
    </p>
    <p>
      This page is also the atlas's manifesto. Two ideas run beneath everything gathered here, and
      rather than stand as essays of their own they are set down once, plainly, as the lens through
      which the rest is meant to be read.
    </p>

    <h2>Every map is an argument</h2>
    <p>
      The guiding idea, drawn from J.B. Harley, is that maps are never neutral. A map is not a
      window onto the world but a made thing — with a maker, a method, and a motive. Every choice to
      measure, name, or bound the world is also a choice about what to leave out, and each omission
      is quiet enough to pass for objectivity. To draw a coastline is to decide where land ends; to
      print a border is to turn an argument into a fact; to centre one meridian is to make
      everywhere else a margin. The map persuades precisely because it looks like a description
      rather than a claim.
    </p>
    <p>
      Reading maps critically means refusing that disguise — asking, of every sheet, not only
      <em>is it accurate?</em> but <em
        >whose purpose does this accuracy serve, and what does it render invisible?</em
      > The essays make those trade-offs visible; the
      <a href="/colophon/">colophon</a> documents the shared meta-lens that lets them be compared.
    </p>

    <h2>The seduction of precision</h2>
    <p>
      The second idea is a caution about the first. Precision is seductive: a finer grid, a truer
      projection, a more exact survey all feel like pure gains, and for centuries the history of
      cartography has been told as a march toward them. But every gain in accuracy, usability, or
      control exacts a quiet sacrifice somewhere else — a living, four-dimensional world traded for
      a legible surface, a negotiated place fixed into a parcel, a plural name overwritten by a
      single official one. The sharper the map, the more confident its silences.
    </p>
    <p>
      Terra Chartarum does not reject precision; it refuses to mistake it for innocence. We treat
      the elegant, authoritative map as the one most worth interrogating — because it is the one
      whose argument is easiest to miss.
    </p>

    <h2>The seven rooms</h2>
    <p>
      To hold these arguments in view, the atlas is arranged not as a list but as a medieval
      cosmography — <a href="/rooms/">seven rooms</a>, each asking a different question of the
      world. Enter a room to read its essays, walk its maps, and see where its borders touch the
      others.
    </p>
    <ul class="rooms-list">
      {
        ROOMS.map((room) => (
          <li>
            <a href={`/rooms/${room.slug}/`}>{room.title}</a>
            <span> — {room.blurb}</span>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>

    <h2>The essays so far</h2>
    <ul class="list">
      {
        essays.map((e) => (
          <li>
            <a href={`/essays/${e.slug}/`}>{e.data.title}</a>
            <span> — {e.data.subtitle}</span>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>

    <h2>A platform, not a one-off</h2>
    <p>
      The portal is built to grow: new essays are added through a documented starter kit and a
      shared component library (radar charts, timelines, comparison sliders), and the atlas is
      designed to host historical GIS layers. If you would like to contribute an essay, start with
      the
      <a href="/colophon/">colophon</a> and the authoring guide.
    </p>
  </section>
</PortalLayout>

<style>
  .prose {
    max-width: 72ch;
    padding-block: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4rem);
  }
  .prose h1 {
    font-size: var(--step-4);
    margin: 0.3rem 0 1.25rem;
  }
  .prose h2 {
    font-size: var(--step-2);
    margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem;
  }
  .prose p {
    margin: 0 0 1.15rem;
  }
  .prose strong {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .rooms-list,
  .list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .rooms-list li,
  .list li {
    padding: 0.5rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
  }
  .rooms-list a,
  .list a {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--step-1);
  }
</style>
